## The Psychedelic Clinical Trials That Could Change Treatment

The past three years have brought a major increase in psychedelic research. This momentum has been driven by [regulatory developments](https://www.thepsychedelicdigest.com/blog/psychedelic-therapy-australia-2026), [investment in psychedelic medicine](https://www.thepsychedelicdigest.com/psyfinance) and growing demand for new mental health treatments.

As of July 2026, more than 100 psychedelic clinical trials are reportedly active worldwide. A smaller group stands out because of its potential to influence treatment for depression, PTSD, addiction and neurodegenerative disease.

**These studies could help determine whether psychedelic-assisted therapies move closer to mainstream clinical care.**

## Psilocybin for Treatment-Resistant Depression

PSILODEP-2 is Monash University's phase 2 randomised controlled trial investigating psilocybin-assisted therapy for treatment-resistant depression.

With 160 participants across several sites, it is described as the largest psilocybin trial conducted in the Southern Hemisphere.

* **Why it matters:** Treatment-resistant depression affects people who do not experience adequate relief from standard treatments. Positive results could support a new option for patients who have limited alternatives.
* **What to watch:** The study is expected to complete in November 2026, with top-line results anticipated in the first quarter of 2027.

## MDMA-Assisted Therapy for PTSD

MAPS-2 is a confirmatory phase 3 trial examining MDMA-assisted therapy for post-traumatic stress disorder.

It follows an earlier phase 3 study in which **67% of participants reportedly no longer met the diagnostic criteria for PTSD after treatment**.

* **Why it matters:** PTSD can be difficult to treat, and some patients discontinue or do not respond to existing therapies. A successful confirmatory trial could strengthen the case for MDMA-assisted therapy as a regulated PTSD treatment.
* **What to watch:** Enrolment is ongoing, with results expected in late 2026 or early 2027.

## LSD for Alcohol Use Disorder

MindMed's phase 2b trial is investigating LSD as a potential treatment for alcohol use disorder.

With 200 participants across seven sites, it is described as the largest LSD study conducted in more than 50 years.

* **Why it matters:** Existing treatments for alcohol use disorder do not work equally well for everyone. LSD-assisted treatment could offer a different approach by combining psychological insight with structured therapeutic support.
* **What to watch:** The study is fully enrolled, with results expected in the fourth quarter of 2026.

## Psilocybin and Alzheimer's Disease

An upcoming phase 2 trial led by Johns Hopkins is expected to explore psilocybin in people with Alzheimer's disease.

Preclinical research suggests that psychedelics may affect neuroplasticity, inflammation and neural connectivity. However, those findings do not yet establish that psilocybin can slow cognitive decline in humans.

* **Why it matters:** This study could provide early evidence about whether psychedelic-related mechanisms have any meaningful role in neurodegenerative disease.
* **What to watch:** Enrolment is expected to begin in late 2026, with data likely to arrive in 2028.

## Why Australia Has Become a Psychedelic Research Hub

Australia is well positioned to contribute to the next phase of psychedelic medicine research.

Its [psychedelic therapy regulations](https://www.thepsychedelicdigest.com/blog/australia-psilocybin-approval-2026), established clinical trial infrastructure and growing interest in innovative mental health treatments have made the country an important research hub.

As of 2026, Australia is reportedly home to more than 25 psychedelic trials involving psilocybin, MDMA, DMT and novel compounds.

This activity could help accelerate global research while giving some Australians earlier access to investigational treatments through approved trials. Read our full guide to the [Australian psychedelic clinical trials landscape](https://www.thepsychedelicdigest.com/blog/psychedelic-trials-australia-2026).

## What These Psychedelic Studies Could Mean for Mental Health

If several of these trials produce strong and reproducible results, mental health care could look very different by 2030.

Potential changes may include:

* More approved psychedelic-assisted treatments for specific conditions
* Greater integration of psychedelic therapy into specialist mental health care
* Expanded professional training and clinical standards
* More insurance and public funding discussions
* New treatment options for people who have not benefited from conventional care

None of these outcomes is guaranteed. The quality of the evidence, safety findings, regulatory decisions, treatment costs and availability of trained clinicians will all shape what happens next.

## FAQ About Psychedelic Clinical Trials

**How many psychedelic clinical trials are active worldwide?**

As of July 2026, more than 100 active trials are reportedly investigating psilocybin, MDMA, LSD, DMT, ketamine and newer psychedelic compounds.

**What is the most advanced psychedelic clinical trial for addiction?**

MindMed's phase 2b LSD trial for alcohol use disorder is one of the largest and most advanced psychedelic studies focused on addiction, with results expected in late 2026.

**Could psychedelic-assisted therapy be covered by insurance?**

Coverage will depend on regulatory approval, the condition being treated, the treatment model and the insurer. Broader coverage is more likely if trials demonstrate meaningful benefits, acceptable safety and cost-effectiveness.

**How can I find psychedelic clinical trials near me?**

Search [ClinicalTrials.gov](https://clinicaltrials.gov/) and the [Australian New Zealand Clinical Trials Registry](https://www.anzctr.org.au/) for recruiting studies. Our guide to [volunteering for psychedelic research in Australia](https://www.thepsychedelicdigest.com/blog/psychedelic-volunteer-australia-2026) explains the process in more detail.

**What is the status of MDMA-assisted therapy for PTSD?**

Confirmatory research is continuing. Future access will depend on trial outcomes, regulatory review and the development of appropriate clinical delivery standards.

